description: Borrowed from Ecclesiastical Latin mystēriarchēs (“one who presides over Christian sacraments”), from Ancient Greek μυστηριάρχης (mustēriárkhēs, “one who rules over religious mysteries”), from μυστήριον (mustḗrion) +‎ -άρχης (-árkhēs), corresponding to mystery +‎ -arch.

entries.meaning: (obsolete outside of fantasy) One who rules over mysteries.
